XPO Logistics terminal XDM experienced a UN1805 Low pH Presoak release from a 15-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-quart of product released to a 3’ x 3’ area of the trailer floor/pallet due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents and soda ash solution were deployed and worked into the impacted area to clean and neutralize the release. The impacted absorbents and pallet wood were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drum of the product was patched with chem tape and placed into a separate 55- gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column199: EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND TRAINING SOLUTIONS, INCORPORATED

column169: Hepaco  was  dispatched  to  the  site.  Upon  the contractor’s  arrival,  personnel  observed  that  the  released  material  impacted  a  2ft-by-2ft  area  of  the terminal floor and estimated that half a gallon of material was released due to damage to the 330-gallon metal  tote.  Hepaco personnel  stated that granular absorbents were deployed prior to their arrival by ESTES terminal personnel and Hepaco deployed additional granular absorbents along with chemical boom. No waste was generated from this response.  A 330-gallon metal tote was ordered and Hepaco returned to the site to transfer the remaining from the damaged tote. The impacted absorbents were recovered and containerized into one 15-gallon metal drum along with the spent PPE.  The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

The driver then called our emergency number and a team was dispatched to the location. The response team found that the lid and ring were no longer seated to the top of the drum and liquid had spilled over the top of the drum. The team then rescued the lid to the drum and cleaned up the material with absorbents and disposed of them in accordance with the regulations. First notification 1427CT Response team arrived 1600CT Clean up was complete 1800CT 1-2 Gallons was released all was contained inside of the trailer.

On February 22, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing UN2491 was damaged in transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. HCE personnel utilized hand tools, absorbents, and soda ash to remediate the ethanolamine solution-impacted trailer floor. All impacted material was collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and the damaged drum was placed into one (1) 95-gallon poly overpack. All waste was staged on site for transport and disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal UDV experienced a UN3093 Ferric Nitrate Solution 41% release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3 ounces of product released to the top of the poly tote and tote body due to a loose and crooked cap. The contractors re-secured the cap back onto the tote and wiped down the poly tote for shipment on. No waste was generated.

column169: At 0825 ET Titan Transfer Inc. contacted ERTS to request assistance with cleaning a 8 gallon release of UN1210-INK- PMC031 DK GRN SDA3C. At 1248 EST, Graymar arrived on site and located the release. At 1320 EST, Graymar confirmed an estimated 8 gallons of PMC031D5 Dark Green SDA3C released. No drains or waterways were impacted.  Newell Technologies, confirmed the product is flammable as a liquid, but once solidified, it is non-hazardous.  GrayMar used absorbents, worked it into the impact, collected and placed into one 55-gal poly drum. The contractor will transport the one drum of spent absorbents to the contractor's shop. The impacted 15 gallon pail of product was placed into an overpack and placed onto the trailer as salvage material.

column169: Driver was starting his trip for the day and when doing his Pre-Trip noticed liquid on the floor of the trailer and called our emergency response line. Call was received at around 1115et. A team was dispatched and was in rout at 1230et, They arrived on scene at 1330et and started the process of getting information and dawning the appropriate PPE to begin the clean up. They had to remove several containers to get to the drum which was near the middle of a 53ft trailer. They found the drum and noted that it had a small hole in the side that the material was leaking out. The drum was put into a salvage drum and the material was cleaned up using absorbent materials and then disposed of properly. This was completed at approximately 1800et. The containers that had to be removed to gain excess were then reloaded and secured for shipment at 1900et.
column170: Better inspection of containers need to be done before loading paying attention to even minor dings and dents. Retraining on Container inspections and closure procedures.

XPO Logistics terminal XFO experienced a UN3082 Caromax 28 release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to a 3’ x 2’ area of the wooden trailer floor and a 1’ x 1’ area of the concrete dock floor due to a crack in the top corner of the tote. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents into (2) 55- gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The county hazmat team also responded in efforts to help contain and confine until the response company arrived onsite.
column170: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their forklifts including the forkblades to help prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring. column169: On 2/8/2024 at approximately 1930, Dangerous Goods Addministration received a call from Employee 3646681 at the hub facility in Miami, reporting condensation developing on the outside of a package.  The shipment consisted of two cans classified as "paint" (according to the marking) packaged in dry ice.  During inspection, the shipment built up frost on the outer packaging.  Further investigation revealed that the package polystyrene lining was damaged, resulting in the condesation buildup.  Additionally, one of the cans spilled due to an apparent damaged closure.  The outer package does not appear to have UN Specification marking.  The shipment has been rejected and is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

On 02-22-2024 a CN mechanical performing an inspection observed that the bottom outlet valve appeared to be wet around the valve of tank car # PROX 45654 along with a strong Ethanol type odor in the area. The employee notified the Transportation Manager who in turn notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The tank car was set out to an isolation track for inspection by a CN emergency response contractor. A CN emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the location for mitigation. Contractor performed an inspection of the tank car and found the bottom outlet valve to be leaking from the threads of the bottom outlet valve cap as a result of the BOV not creating a proper seal and the BOV cap not tight enough to contain the leak. (The BOV cap was found to be less than tool tight and the BOV valve in the closed position and pinned upon initial inspection). HMR did observe cable seals to be correctly in place. The BOV valve handle was cycled several times to the open and closed position to free any debris that may have been trapped in the BOV sealing surface potentially causing the leak. The BOV cap was then removed and observed for 20 minutes to ensure there was no further leakage from the valve. It was noted that the BOV cap gasket was deformed and was replaced. The bottom outlet valve cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench. Upon tightening the BOV cap, Contractor proceeded to place new cable seals on the BOV / Cap.

column169: On 02/15/2024, during the boarding phase of flight DL2019, a passenger's carry-on bag in the overhead bin went into thermal runaway. The Flight Attendants heard a"pop" and saw flames in the overhead bin at row 11. Flight Attendants initiated an evacuation using the jetway. Customer removed the bag from the overhead and stepped on it to extinguish the fire. The flight attendants were on their way to retrieve the containment bag/water. ARFF responded, determined multi loose Li-ion batteries and coins arched and started the fire. No fire extinguisher or 02 masks were used. The affected overhead bin has no damage other than smoke soot residue. No Flight Attendant or customer injuries were reported. The NRC and FAA were notified.
column170: The Flight Attendant followed established procedures and placed the item in a fire containment bag and applied water to mitigate the remaining smoke.

On February 9, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of NA1993 was punctured in transit due to no dunnage and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel secured the damaged tote and proceeded to transfer the NA1993 to one (1) new 330-gallon poly tote that was fitted with the appropriate labels for further shipment and processing. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the released product in the trailer and swept them in with hand tools. The one (1) empty and damaged tote was cut up with hand tools. Two (2) 55-gallon poly drums of spent absorbents, PPE, the cut-up tote, and any cleanup debris were generated as waste and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

On February 22, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1755 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. HCE personnel deployed neutralizing, granular absorbents to the released product and swept them in with hand tools. The other tote on the shipment was wiped down with a neutralizing solution and absorbent pads. All spent absorbents, PPE, and any cleanup debris were collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums that were labeled appropriately and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

On February 28, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of power-max plus (NA1993) was damaged by a forklift and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. HCE personnel containerized the one (1) 55-gallon damaged metal drum into an overpacked metal drum.  The utilized PPE waste was containerized to one (1) 5-gallon bucket.  All waste generated was staged on site for further handling.

Driver was stopping at the end of his day and was completing the Post-trip inspection when noticed liquids drippings from trailer onto his tire at 1800. The driver grabed some absorbent to contain the liquid and called our emergency response at 1806. A team was dispatched out to address the release 1830. The crew arrived on scene at around 1900 and added more absorbents to provide a containment and monitoring. Equipment was need to gain access to the containers as the trailer was double stacked and full. The equipment was on scene by 0700 and unloading began. The container was reached by 0900 and found that there was a small dent in the bottom chime which a small hole was found. The material was cleaned up using absorbent pads and was disposed of per the proper requirements. The trailer was then reloaded and secured by around 1700 and driver was sent on his way.

On Sunday, Febuary 25, 2024, a CN mechanical performing an inspection observed that the bottom outlet valve appeared to be leaking from tank car # GBRX 703408 along with a strong Ethanol type odor in the area. The employee notified the Transportation Manager who in turn notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The tank car was set out to an isolation track (WA90) for inspection by a CN emergency response contractor. A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The contractor performed an inspection of the tank car and found the bottom outlet valve to be leaking from the threads of the bottom outlet valve cap. It was determined that there was a failure in the sealing surface of the valve seat to include a defective gasket. (The BOV cap was found to be tool tight and the BOV in the closed position and pinned upon initial inspection). CN emergency response contractor did observe cable seal to be correctly in place. The BOV valve handle was cycled several times to the open and closed position to free any debris that may have been trapped in the BOV sealing surface potentially causing the leak. The BOV cap was then removed and observed for 20 minutes to ensure there was no further leakage from the valve. It was noted that the BOV cap gasket was deformed and was replaced. The bottom outlet valve cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench. Upon tightening the BOV cap, CN emergency response contractor proceeded to place new cable seals on the BOV / Cap.

column169: On 2/6/2024 at approximately 1830, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 4346935 is the station location in Hampton, reporting an undeclared dangerous goods shipment.  The package consisted of one fiberboard box, containing an inner fiberboard box with a glass bottle inside.  The attached paperwork identifies the commodity as "Hydrogen Sulfide", prompting the opening of the shipment for verification.  The package was not prepared with the required DG markings, labeling, or paperwork, in accordance with IATA regulations and is being held, pending an FAA investigation.  UPDATE:  Further review revealed a misclassification of the commodity.  The commodity appears to be identified as "fuel oil" and as requesting that test be conducted using "hydrogen sulfide".  The spill incident is being resubmitted with the updated classification.

column169: Company Fuel Driver was making a fuel delivery at store at 09:03am, the driver had two hoses of connected from the trailer belly valves to the underground fuel storage tank(UST). Cones were in place to protect the area as well as lights activated for warnings. A white pickup truck(Super Duty) bearing Maryland registration# 9EC0549, pulling a - cement mixer trailer, disregarded the activated lights and orange security cones of our vehicle; drove over the hose fitting connected to the UST and tore the fitting and the lip of the UST off the tank. The hose attached to the trailer UST became stuck under the pickup truck. The driver exited their truck and removed the hose from under his truck; and left the scene immediately. Police report was filed with VA State Police(Trooper J.B. Moore) for truck"leaving th€ scene of the accident". Fuel driver managed to capture a photo of the truck that ran over the fitting and hoses and reported the incident to Law Enforcement and the Safety Department immediately. Material spilled was contained by the fuel driver using absorbent pads, and emptied the remaining fuel in the hose into the UST. No fuel contaminated the ground nor entered into any water systems.
column170: No recommendations for improvement to prevent this incident as our driver had properly secured the scene prior to delivery, had warning lights active and was attentive to his surroundings.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel collected one (1) damaged 5-gallon pail of UN3098 for disposal. Crews then deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and pavement and worked them in utilizing hand tools. Once collected, FCE personnel utilized a neutralizing agent and absorbent pads to collect all residual product. All UN3098 impacted material was collected and containerized in three (3) 55-gallon drums that were staged onsite for disposal by R+L.

On February 22, 2024, two (2) 50-pound bags of UN3378 were damaged in transit and released approximately one (1) pound of product to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to remediate the impacted site. Crews utilized a HEPA vacuum to collect all free-standing product. The contents of the vacuum, the damaged bags, and all UN3378 impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal. The drum was properly labeled, and possession of the material was taken by RLC to be disposed of through their bulk waste stream.

Driver 18151 was dispatched for a load going to Lake Park Mobil but was given a customer information sheet for Northlake Mobil. Driver did not catch this mistake and went to the wrong location. Once he arrived, he obtained an ATG reading that verified his load would not fit. The driver overfilled the tank and this resulted in a spill that impacted a drain. After investigating this with the APEC rep it was determined that the Reg tank was able to hold an additional 200 gallons of regular. Because the tanks are manifolded the rest of the product flowed into the premium tank. Only approximately 12 gallons of product was actually spilled. CDG managed the response and cleanup.

column169: A Veolia employee was at the customer site loading flammable liquid into the tanker truck. Once the truck was loaded, the Veolia driver communicated to the customer that the loading process was complete. While shutting down the pumping operations the customer did not follow the proper shutdown sequence and prematurely closed the internal valve on the tank the flammable liquid was pumped from. This action increased the pressure on the vapor recovery line and resulted in blowing the line off the valve of the tank truck releasing a mist of flammable liquid.
column170: An investigation was completed and identified that the customer employee disregarded the procedures to properly shut down a tanker pump. On February 15, 2204, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1219 had a faulty cap during transit and released approximately 165-gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted surface and worked them in with hand tools. A forklift provided by RLC was used to gravity transfer the remaining product from the one (1) damaged 330-gallon tote into one (1) new 330-gallon tote. Absorbent pads and cleaners were used to remove all residual product from the impacted surfaces. All UN1219-impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) 5-gallon pail for disposal purposes.

Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of material released to a 12’ x 2’ area of the trailer floor and a 10’ x 10’ area of the concrete lot underneath the trailer due to a pinhole puncture. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Citric acid solution and absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the release. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all spent absorbents into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Truck and trailer with hazardous waste load on a van trailer were in route. This load contained metal drums of waste flammable liquid. Driver stopped to take a break at a rest area in KY and discovered that there was a leak coming from the rear of the trailer. Local Fire Dept and Police were dispatched to the scene. An emergency response company was also retained and dispatched to the scene for response and clean up. For precaution the Fire Department evacuated the rest area. Upon investigation it was determined that one of the metal drums had been punctured and had leaked out inside the trailer and them some had leaked from the rear of the trailer onto the ground.  The trailer was unloaded and decontaminated and the punctured drum was placed in an overpack and loaded back onto the trailer along with the other drums. The response crew also cleaned up the small amount that reached the ground. All waste was placed back on the trailer and transported to destination.

column169: Driver of bobtail truck meets oncoming dump truck on narrow roadway and moves slightly to the right side to avoid striking mirrors. The rear tires of the bobtail truck leave the edge of the roadway and pulls the truck into the berm. Immediately after the oncoming truck passes the bobtail driver corrects his line of travel back up on the road surface.  and crosses the left lane, out of control, and leaves the pavement into the ditch, striking a group of trees.  During the impact, a section of piping for propane vapor on the rear of the bobtail is sheared off, resulting in a propane release.  The driver was able to slow the leak at the cargo tank within 5 minutes by reseating the excess flow valve where the piping had been sheared off.   A secondary bobtail truck responded to the scene and was able to safely empty the damaged bobtail by transferring the propane into the secondary truck.  The damaged bobtail was towed to an impound lot that evening.  The remaining propane vapor in the cargo tank was flared off the following day.

column169: On2/9/2024 at approximately 1730, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 4009660 at the station location in Jamaica, NY, reporting a corrosive spill.  The shipment consists of 3 fiberboard boxes, each marked as "Excepted Quaniities" and each containing a cylinder.  One of the boxes leaked during transport.  Further inspection revealed that the closure appeared bent, resulting in spillage.  Upon obtaining the UN classification of the Hazard class 8 substance from the shipper, it was determined that the commodity may have exceeded the maximum allowable amount for excepted quantities, according to IATA Regulations. An estimated 4000 mL of liquid was discovered in each cylinder.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

column169: RSR Crew was inspecting a set of cars in Silver Springs Siding that NS had set out.  Crew noticed car #UTLX 209221 leaking diesel fuel and immediately notified RSR Trainmaster, Matthew Quattrone and Director Environmental Rita Mager.  Car UTLX 209221 was set out by NS about 12 hours before RSR crew got there and were not sure how long it had been leaking.  It was a slow leak - about 1 drop every 12 to 15 seconds.  RSR Crew contained the spill.  Rita Mager contacted SPSI who responded to site for repairs to car.  Per SPSI, repairs noted as 'Tightened the packing nut of the valve stem packing to stop the leak."  Report sent to car owner, who issued the OTMA.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred. During product handling at the Wilbur-Ellis' facility in Rosebud, TX. A Wilbur-Ellis' employee was moving a 250-gallon tote containing Grayzon Next Herbicide when he cut a turn short, resulting in a puncture to the bottom of the tote. Approximately 250 gallons of free product released, mostly inside of secondary containment. A small amount of the product, approximately 20 gallons, escaped secondary containment, with 15 gallons hitting concrete, and 5 gallons hitting gravel. There was no reported impact to water. There were no reported injuries or exposures. Wilbur-Ellis' personnel reviewed the SOS and responded with appropriate PPE. The product from the impacted tote was recovered and placed into a secondary tote. The impacted gravel and free product was recovered into containers, and will be disposed of via the facility's waste stream.
column170: Since the release was accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Wilbur Ellis Company will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column169: Driver arrived at customer to fill a Ammonia Tank. He verified everything on the BulldMiniBulk Checklist to verify all connections and tank was ready to complete off load. Customer signed off before the off load. Customer and driver gave each other thumbs up from a distance. The driver thought that was an indication good to start the pump off. Shortly after driver started the pump, he heard a boom noise, exited the truck and noticed the product Ieaking from the pump. He imniediately turned off the pump. The customer notified his team and the product was contained and cleaned on site immediately. The cause of the release was determined to be the customer had not released the internal valve and water in the dyke area causing deadhead back to the pump. Univar maintenance and Vendor maintenance determined the vibration and stress caused a crack in suction pipe into pump causing the leak. The crack was welded and further tests on pipe and pump resulted in no further leaks or releases.
column170: dyke area causing deadhead pressure back to the pump. Univar maintenance and Vendor maintenance determined the vibration and stress caused a crack in suction pipe causing the leak. The crack was welded and further tests on pipe and pump resulted in no further leaks or releases. We're also furthering the PM schedule for pumps and tests to review connections and pipes.

column169: On February 12, 2024, twenty-four (24) 12-ounce cans of aerosol paint (UN1263) were punctured by a forklift and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the cardboard box and trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the impacted site. Crews utilized absorbent pads to collect all freestanding product, and any residual material was removed with a degreasing agent. All spent absorbent pads and impacted cardboard were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, and the damaged cans were collected and containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon drum. The drums were properly labeled and possession of the material was taken by R+L for disposal through their bulk waste stream.

On February 10, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of UN1760 was damaged due to unknown causes and released approximately seven (7) gallons of product to the trailer floor, lift gate, wood, and asphalt ground. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration, LLC (ER) to remediate the impacted site.  Crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and worked them in with hand tools. A hose was utilized to perform a gravity transfer to remove the remaining product from the damaged tote into a new tote provided by ER. The new tote was properly labeled and left on-site for disposal. Crews dismantled the damaged tote and impacted wooden pallet with hand tools for disposal purposes. All spent absorbents, impacted pallet, and tote were collected and containerized into five (5) 55-gallon drums for disposal.

During sport operations at the EWRH facility a drum was discovered leaking. The bottom chime was damaged resulting in a release of contents. the drum was placed into a steel salvage package and a new declaration will be obtained for movement.

On February 26, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3267 was damaged in transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the pallet, trailer, and parking lot. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE crews deployed a neutralizing solution to the impacted areas until a neutral pH was confirmed. Granular absorbents were deployed and worked in with hand tools. The undamaged cargo was repalletized for transport with the driver back to the Wilmington, OH terminal. The damaged drum was collected and containerized into one (1) 85-gallon overpack drum, and all UN3267-impacted material was collected and containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon drum. All generated waste was staged on-site.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. The damaged super sack was patched, wrapped in poly sheeting and taken to be shrink wrapped to continue on to its destination. All waste was collected and containerized into one (1) 15-gallon poly vented drum and staged on site for transport and disposal.

column169: Enviroserve was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed  that the released material impacted  a 5ft-by-10ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that eighteen (18) ounces of material was released due to forklift damaging one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. Enviroserve personnel deployed absorbent pads to the impacted area and  gathered  the  spent  absorbents. On 2/12/2024, I john Vergis Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE, was called by the WLE Car Shop Manager @0730 hrs. about tank car UTLX 205661 leaking in the WLE Rook Yard.  When I arrived to look at the car, I could see that is was leaking product from the protective housing on top the car.  I got on top the car and removed seal number 451443 from the protective housing cover and noticed that product was leaking from the Sample Line Valve.   Product was leaking from the valve plug.  I checked to see of the valve handle was shut and it was not tight.  I turned the valve handle one complete turn before it was shut tight.  I then checked to see if the valve plug was loose and when I touched the plug, it fell out.  I installed new thread sealant on the plug and installed it in the valve and tightened it tool tight.  I then cleaned off the top and sides of the car the best I could.  I installed new seal number 0000225 on the protective housing lid and then released the car back into transportation.

column169: On 2/3/2024, at 0230 hours, personnel in the CSXT Yoeman Yard, in Tampa, Florida, reported tank car RCRX 2714, load, hydrochloric acid, was leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Daikin America, Inc., was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-0203-00008). Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, and Josh Dearing, a CSX Manager of Hazardous Materials, were dispatched to the scene.  Response personnel found that 1 of 4 liquid line closure flange bolts were less than tool tight.  Response personnel properly tightened the liquid line closure flange bolts and stopped the release.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Scott Missildine, 256-476-8009).  Additionally, response personnel verified proper securement of all other closure bolts on the tank car’s service equipment, removed hazardous residue from the exterior of the car, and applied a mild neutralizing agent to the car’s surface prior to releasing the car for transportation.

column169: DURING CLEAN UP AND INSPECTION RESPONDER DISCOVERED UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. ETHANOL SOLUTION

On 2/20/24, at 1316 hours, personnel in the CSXT Radnor Yard discovered TILX270130, a loaded tank car of Hexamethylenediamine, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and shipper, Ascend Performance Materials, were notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-02-20-00151). Marion Environmental Inc., a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 4 of the 4 liquid valve mounting flange bolts were less than tool tight.  MEI personnel tightened the flange bolts to secure the release.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Tara Gardner, tgardn@ascendmaterials.com, 256-552-2528).  The car was held at Radnor pending further repair and qualification by certified repair unit.

column169: Valve Damage/Failure

On February 23, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of UN3266 had a faulty valve and released approximately one hundred (100) gallons of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Indian Spill Response (ISR) to remediate the impacted site.  Crews deployed granular absorbents and a neutralizing agent to the impacted dock and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into five (5) 55-gallon drums. Crews transferred the product from the damaged 275-gallon tote into a new one 275-gallon tote. Crews cut up the damaged tote and placed the contents into one (1) 55-gallon drum. All containers were staged onsite for future disposal.

column169: On 02/01/2024, at 0900 hours, personnel in the CSXT Collinwood Yard discovered MJEX 73527, a loaded tank car of Methyl Isobutyl Carbinol, leaking from the manway area.  The car was isolated and The Shipper, Altivia, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-0201-00063). EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the product leaking from the liquid line valve mounting flange as a result of the mounting flange bolts being less than tool tight. Contractor personnel tightened the flange bolts to stop the release. The issue identified and corrective action were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Timothy Albert, 740-533-5200). The car was held out of transportation pending further repair/qualification by a certified mobile repair unit or One Time Movement Approval (OTMA) from FRA.

column169: The transport was headed West on HWY 39 when the driver turned to enter the Enable Naples unload station, Crude Oil began to spill along side the trailer. The transport stopped and proceeded to call his supervisor. When the supervisor arrived, along with internal environmental personnel it was determined that driver was responsible for the spill.  The driver did admit he had failed to close the fire valve and vent line valve on his trailer.   The environmental clean up crew and local authorities were alerted. The environmental crew arrived at 7:53am.  They spread powder absorbent on the highway and used a street sweeper to cleanup the residue.  No waste was generated and no manifest produced for disposal. Work was completed at 8:33am.  There was a local sheriff vehicle at the intersection at  5am but they left as soon as CRCT personnel arrived.  No other authorities from Grady County were ever on site.
column170: Driver was coached on how to properly close all valves on the trailer. The field supervisors have done multiple field inspections on this driver since the event to ensure the proper procedures are being followed.

column169: Post-incident inspection revealed a malfunctioning vapor recovery system on the 87E10 storage tank at the delivery location. The spill was the result of the delivery driver improperly disconnecting the delivery coupling while the system was pressurized. The pressure equalized after 4-5 minutes and the overfill subsided. Local EMS responded as did a professional response team to mitigate the effects of the release. The released gasoline entered the stormwater retention basin at the delivery site and just into the outflow area on the property. The spill did not leave the premises. No surface water or ground water was impacted.
column170: The location storage system has been repaired, and the delivery driver has received re-training to reinforce the driver's understanding of the company procedures for situations where product ceases to flow during delivery.

column169: On 02/14/2024 at 1812, personnel in the CSXT Acca Yard reported UTLX 210839, a loaded tank car of Alcohols N.O.S., was suspected to be leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Valero Marketing, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2024-02-14-00201). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, and Blaise MacDonald, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, were dispatched to the scene and found the manway cover was mis-aligned allowing the release; additionally,  seven out of eight manway cover bolts were less than tool tight. Response personnel inspected the manway cover gasket and properly secured the manway cover for transportation.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Judy Watson 210-934-8157).

column169: AT THE UPS FACILITY IN NASSAU, NEW YORK, SMOKE WAS OBSERVED EMITTING FROM A ONE POUND FIBERBOARD BOX. EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED FROM THE AREA AND THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED OUTSIDE. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS VISIBLE ON THE OUTER BOX. THERE IS AN APPLIED LABEL STATING "DO NOT THROW AWAY THIS BOX. PLEASE PLACE THE CAMERA BACK IN THIS BOX AFTER REMOVING IT FROM THE WALL". "KEPLER ANALYTICS" IS ALSO INDICATED ON ONE SIDE OF THE BOX. THE EVENT HAS CAUSED ONE SIDE OF THE BOX TO HAVE A BURN HOLE WITH SCORCH MARKS SURROUNDING. THERE ARE VISIBLE CHAR AND SCORTCH MARKS ON ANOTHER SIDE OF THE BOX. INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENT REVEALS SOME TYPE OF CAMERA WITH AN UNKNOWN BATTERY SOURCE THAT IS ALMOST ENTIRELY DESTROYED. PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT, THE PACKAGE WAS FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT FROM FT LAUDERDALE (FLL) TO LOUISVILLE (SDF) TO NEW YORK (JFK). AS REQUIRED PER 171.15 A TELEPHONE NOTICE WAS MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC). REPORT NUMBER 1392059.

On 02-24-2024 a CN transportation employee observed liquid dripping down the side of tank car # UTLX 125078 (Loaded - Spent Sulfuric Acid - UN ID - 1832 - Class 8) while performing switching operations at the CN Geismar Yard located in Geismar, LA. The employee notified the CN Transportation Manager who in turn notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team for an emergency response. The responding CN Dangerous Goods Officer performed an inspection of the tank car and noted spillage on the BL side of the car and liquid dripping the eduction line securement flange. Further inspection revealed: (1) of the (4) flange securement fasteners was not properly tightened and could be freely moved by hand. The 1" air valve was in the completely open position with its securement plug securely installed. The 2" liquid eduction line securement cap was less than tool tight (could be turned by hand. The loose liquid eduction line cap was the source of the leak. The tank car's internal pressure was relieved through the 1" air valve stopping the leak. The Liquid eduction line securement cap was properly tightened with an 18" pipe wrench. The 1" air valve was closed, and its securement plug was properly tightened with an 18" pipe wrench. The tank car was then decontaminated by a CN hired contractor. A contractor hired by the responsible party replaced all (4) liquid eduction line flange bolts and securement nuts. The tank car was then pressured up to 10 PSI with a standard air compressor and inspected for leaks. No leaks were discovered.

CN Transportation employee observed liquid coming from the top of tank car TILX 726166 while performing switching operations at the CN Proctor yard, Duluth, MN. The employee notified the employee in charge who then notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team and CN Environment to investigate.  A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location and found (2) of the (6) manway cover swing bolts to be loose (could turn by hand) preventing a proper seal of the gasket allowing the contents to leak out when the car moved. Both the liquid and vapor line vale securement plugs were found tool tight. The shipper security seals were found to be intact at the time of inspection.  The security seals were removed from the manway cover and the protective housing cover. The manway cover was opened to inspect the gasket which was found to be in good condition. The manway cover was closed, and all swing bolts were properly tightened. The valve securement plugs were inspected and found tool tight. New security seals were applied. The exterior of the tank car was cleaned off utilizing a degreaser and rags.

column59: Bottom Outlet Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve
column63: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column169: On 2/6/2024 a SOO Line Railroad (DBA CPKC) Hazardous Materials Officer, Anthony Houdyshell, became  aware that FRA Inspector Daniel Perkins had performed a hazmat inspection at the CPKC CORDOVA SPUR  TRACK, in CORDOVA, IL. During the Inspection Mr. Perkins cited ECUX 461228 because it was leaking  OCTYL ALCOHOL from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) threads past the BOV cap. Estimated release was  less than 0.5 gallon. A railroad qualified response contractor was mobilized to investigate and  mitigate the leak.  Upon arrival, responders found ECUX 46 1228 with a BOV not secured tool tight, and the presence of  product weeping around the threads of the BOV cap. The BOV was in the fully closed position, but  responders observed that the four-inch bottom outlet ball valve had a small amount of product on  the 8-L side of the ball. 1-2 drops fell every 2-3 minutes. Additionally, the four inch bottom  outlet flange gasket was observed to be out of round and slightly warped, although the release was  not related to the warped gasket. The BOV cap was tightened tool tight with PTFE tape to stop the  weeping. The response contractor placed an out of service tag on the BOV, and applied HOMESHOP  stickers to both sides of the tank car.  The contractor climbed ECUX 461228 and observed the manway with a single loose manway swing bolt.  The manway cover seal was cut, all swing bolts loosened, and the manway opened. The manway gasket  was verified in good condition. The manway was then closed, and the manway swing bolts were secured  to tool tight.  Responders returned to Cordova, IL on the following day and verified that ECUX 461228 was not  leaking prior to the car being switched into the 3M facility. This move (400 ft) was made under the  emergency provisions of 174.5, with a verbal notification made by Houdyshell to FRA. The car was  subsequently unloaded by 3M and then an OTMA was obtained to move the car to home shop by  ExxonMobil.  File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at  the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a "bulk" shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column170: The SOO LINE RAILROAD COMPANY (DBA CPKC) notified shipper of this release. Continued emphasis is made with Offerors/Shippers to conduct thorough inspections prior to movement in order to reduce valve failures In the field. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For NARs (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper Is requested to conduct a root-cause Investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with CPKC. Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Tony Houdyshell, SOO Line Railroad, 120 S 6th ST STE 900, Minneapolis, MN 55402. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. (NAR: 547)

column43: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column169: SequenceEvent: Package was found wet and torn open from leaking contents. Package was placed into a haz bag and tote. Tote was taken to a QA area. DescribePack: 1 lead acid battery was leaking from top seams. Box had deflated air bags and insufficient packing material resulting in battery moving around inside box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Battery was adjusted to prevent further leakage and placed into a second haz bag.

column43: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column169: BNSF Mechanical identified a possible release from top of car while switching. Graymar Env was mobilized to inspect and identified two man way swing bolts requiring 4 full rotations to secure. Shipper notified once release was confirmed. Release has been secured for continued movement.
column170: Ensure the tank car is secured prior to offering for transport.(NAR:200)

column169: CONTENTS OF AN AIR PACKAGE SHIPPED FROM COLOMBIA TO THE USA WERE INSPECTED DUE TO A STRONG ACETONE ODOR COMING FROM THE PACKAGE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, ONE CONTAINER OF LUMELI REMOVEDOR DE ESMALTE TRANSLATED AS LUMELI NAIL POLISH REMOVER WAS FOUND LEAKING. THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE PACKAGE WITH JUST A SMALL STAIN ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN PREVIOUSLY INSPECTED BY CUSTOMS OFFICIALS IN MIAMI PRIOR TO BEING RELEASED INTO THE UPS NETWORK. THERE IS "OPENED FOR CUSTOMS PURPOSES" TAPE SURROUNDING THE PACKAGE AND SURROUNDING THE LUMELI NAIL POLISH REMOVER INSIDE THE BOX. THE PACKAGE SCANS IN THE UPS NETWORK AS UPS SMALL PACKAGE TRACKING 1ZB6864V0423811919 BUT ALL THERMAL TRACKING LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE SHOW COLOMBIA NATIONAL POSTAL SERVICE, 4-72, TRACKING NUMBER CP0051323737CO. THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FROM COLOMBIA USING UPS ACCOUNT B6864V, ANICAM COLOMBIA SAS, TV 93 #53-32 BODEGA 13, PARQUE EMPRESARIAL EL DORADO, BOGOTA DC 110911 COLOMBIA.
